SIMPLE: innocent
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Innocent
<hw>In"no*cent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>innocent</ets>, L. <ets>innocens</ets>, <ets>-entis</ets>; pref.
<ets>in-</ets> not + <ets>nocens</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>nocere</ets> to
harm, hurt. See <er>Noxious</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Not harmful;
free from that which can injure; innoxious; innocuous; harmless; <as>as,
an <ex>innocent</ex> medicine or remedy</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The spear⟦br⟧
Sung <qex>innocent</qex>, and spent its force in air.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Morally free from guilt; guiltless; not tainted with
sin; pure; upright.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To offer up a weak, poor, <qex>innocent</qex> lamb.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have sinned in that I have betrayed the <qex>innocent</qex>
blood.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xxvii. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The aidless, <qex>innocent</qex> lady, his wished prey.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Free from the guilt of a particular crime or
offense; <as>as, a man is <ex>innocent</ex> of the crime
charged</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Innocent</qex> from the great transgression.</q> <rj><qau>Ps.
xix. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Simple; artless; foolish.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Lawful; permitted; <as>as, an <ex>innocent</ex>
trade</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Not contraband; not subject to forfeiture; <as>as,
<ex>innocent</ex> goods carried to a belligerent nation</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Innocent party</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>,<cd>a party who
has not notice of a fact tainting a litigated transaction with
illegality.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Harmless; innoxious; innoffensive; guiltless;
spotless; immaculate; pure; unblamable; blameless; faultless; guileless;
upright.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Innocent</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Innocent
<hw>In"no*cent</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An innocent person;
one free from, or unacquainted with, guilt or sin.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An unsophisticated person; hence, a child; a
simpleton; an idiot.</def> <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In Scotland a natural fool was called an <qex>innocent</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Innocents' day</b></col> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld>,
<cd>Childermas day.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Innocently</ent>⟦br⟧
